author: SixInSixtySix
body:
I’m looking at my W4 through ADP and the only options I have are:

Enter expected child tax credit related to dependents: $0

Enter estimated full year non-wage income not subject to withholding: $0

Enter estimated full-year deductions above standard deduction amount: $0

Additional amount, if any, you want withheld from each paycheck: $0

I can change all of those numbers, but have to sign an “under penalty of perjury I agree that this is all true” thing at the bottom.





How do I make it so $0 comes out of my paycheck and I just pay it all later?

author: pretentiousilliterat
body:
I am 30 years old and my company provides an SEP with Charles Schwab. They contribute about 10% annually. My annual salary is $200k. I haven’t been with the company for very long so this year they put $6400 in to the SEP account and it is just sitting there. I’m looking for advice because I have no idea what I’m doing.

I’m willing to be a little bit risky with my money, but not willing to lose more than 50% of this initial investment.

I have a wife and baby. Wife stays at home, so no additional income. We are also looking to buy a house in the near future, so we are saving for a down payment.

I also have a 401k with ADP that was managed by someone else. It has about $30k in it.

I don’t know what to do as far as stocks, bonds, or mutual funds go. I have never decided exactly where to put my investments on my own. Any recommendations or advice is appreciated. If you have reading material you recommend that’s awesome too!
